We will be hosting registration for these classes only at Morning Sun Elementary in the lunchroom on Monday, July 27th, from 3:00 PM-6:30 PM. At this time, there will be paperwork to fill out. post_text:
Our PTO has been a great support of Morning Sun Elementary. With the school year ending and PTO not able to host some of their fundraisers, the Morning Sun Staff felt we should have one for them. After all they do so much for us we can do a little in return.
If you have watched the elite documentary on Netflix called "The Tiger King" you know three items of information -
1. You can buy a cub tiger for around $2,000.
2. Rubbing sardine oil on a person can cause a tiger to eat them.
3. This isn't the original Tiger King. The Original Tiger King resides in Morning Sun, Iowa and he has been here since 1974.
We created a shirt celebrating "The Original Tiger King"
All proceeds will go to our Morning Sun PTO to help them on some of the fundraisers they missed out on this spring.

https://anywearmp.com/collections/the-original-tiger-king

May 26, 2020 Update:

Some random social distancing information for you today. Many people have a hard time picturing six feet, so here are some things to help you determine if you are maintaining the correct amount of social distance. 6 feet is the same as: the typical refrigerator after you have pushed it over; the average couch, provided your children have not ruined it by playing "quarantine tag"; 2 adult cats stretched end to end; and, of course, one Iowa State Fair Butter Cow.

In addition to maintaining the same distance as two adult cats stretched end to end, remember all the recommendations:

Wash your hands.
Cover your cough.
Wash your hands.
Stay home if you are ill.
Wash your hand.
Practice social distancing.
Wash your hands.

Stay strong, everyone.

With the current restrictions and safety concerns for our staff, our Preschool sign up will take place by Google Form.

1. Students must be 4 before the first day of school.
2. By state law, we are limited to 20 students.
-Preference is given to Morning Sun district residents or those who have siblings in the building
-Next, student enrolling from Wapello and Winfield-Mt. Union
-5 year old may participate as long as we are under the 20 student limit

If you have any questions, email nathan.carlson@mscsd.org

March 11, 2020 Update:

The weather yesterday felt like a day in late fall, rather than spring. I'm really hoping it was a fluke.

Governor Reynolds hinted that she will reveal some details tomorrow about continued reopening efforts. I have no idea what those details might be. Time will tell.

I will be out of commission for a couple days, so there won't be any daily updates. Fear not. They shall return.

In the meantime...

Wash your hands.
Cover your cough.
Wash your hands.
Stay home if you belong to a high risk group.
Wash your hands.
If you are out and about, practice social distance. For you State Fair fans, social distancing means keep one butter cow distance from other people.
Wash your hands.

Stay strong, everyone.

post_text:
May 7, 2020 Update:

***Kids, I hope all of you washed your feet after reading yesterday's update. If not, wash them especially well tonight!

***The May board meeting will be Monday, at 6:00. It will be held remotely. Meeting information will be on the school's website if you would like to log in and observe the meeting.

***Happy Teacher and Staff Appreciation Week to everyone! Thank you to everyone for all of your hard work. Much of it is behind the scenes and not always visible, but it is appreciated all the same.

***Today, the guidelines are presented to you in Esperanto. This language was created in the late 1800s and was supposed to become the universal language that replaced all of the other languages on the planet. Yeah, well, that was a big failure. But, the language lives on. Enjoy.

Lavu viajn manojn.
Kovru vian tuson.
Lavu viajn manojn.
Restu hejme.
Lavu viajn manojn.
Praktiku socian distancadon.
Lavu viajn manojn.

Stay strong, everyone!

No new announcements from the governor today.

So, since there isn't much new information, I decided to share a gross fact with everyone. Did you know that, on average, your feet have over 250,000 sweat glands and give off almost 1 cup of sweat EACH DAY? Something to ponder...

And while you're pondering...

Wash your hands.
Cover your cough.
Wash your hands.
Stay home. Resist the temptation. Stay home.
Wash your hands.
If you leave home, practice social distancing.
Wash your hands.

Stay strong, everyone.

post_text:
May 4, 2020 update:

No new information from today's press conference.

Be sure to check out the video that was recently posted on the school's facebook page. Apparently, the kids aren't the only ones going a little stir crazy these days!

When I was an English teacher, I would sometimes challenge my students to complete a piece of writing without using a certain letter of the alphabet. Some letters were easier than others. I asked Matthew to pick a letter of the alphabet at random. Of course, he picked the letter "E." So, here is my attempt to give today's guidelines without using the letter "E."

Wash your hands.
Cloak your cough.
Wash your hands.
Stay in your accommodations. Stay in your lodgings. Stay in your pad.
Wash your hands.
If you must go from your lodgings, apply social distancing.
Wash your hands.

Isolation does strange things to one's brain.

Stay strong, everyone.

April 30, 2020 Update:

Remember breakfast/lunch pickup is tomorrow at 9:00.

Keep working hard, kids. The weather is nice, but don't let school fall by the wayside. Also, be nice to the people taking care of you. Just a friendly reminder as COVID-19 enters what feels like its 4 millionth day.

And now, today's health guidelines shall be presented to you in the form of poetry. Specifically, that very popular poetic form...the limerick. Feel free to read out loud to get the full effect.

When you're washing your hands on this day...Please remember at home you should stay...Because when the sun glows...And the cool breezes blow...It's so hard to keep COVID at bay.

Stay strong, everyone.

April 28, 2020 Update:

Happy Tuesday, everyone!

No new school announcements from the governor today. She did confirm that she is lifting the ban on in-person worship services throughout the entire state. Yesterday, there was some confusion about this question, so I was glad she clarified things today.

Remember that breakfast/lunch will be available for pickup tomorrow starting at 9:00.

And now, we are going to have today's guidance provided in Ubbi Dubbi. Yes, that is an actual language, according to Google.

Wubash yubour hubands
Cubover yubour cubough
Wubash yubour hubands
Stubay hubome. Thubis mubeans yubou
Wubash yubour hubands
Ubif yubou mubust trubavubel prubactubice subocubiubal dubistubancubing
Wubash yubour hubands

Yes, social distancing is getting to all of us!

Stay strong, everyone.

April 27, 2020 Update:

***Governor Reynolds has taken steps to start "opening up" portions of the state. However, Louisa County is not one of those areas. As of now, the restrictions for Louisa County and other areas with high case numbers remain in place. She did say that May 15 would, hopefully, see another round of openings.

***Remember that breakfast and lunch pickups are Mondays, Wednesdays, and Fridays at 9:00 each day. This is available for anyone aged 0-19, even if you don't go to school in Morning Sun.

***Keep your brains working, kids. Lots of learning that you can be doing. School buildings are closed. School is not.

***Wash your hands.
Cover your cough.
Wash your hands.
Stay home. Stay home. Stay home.
Wash your hands.
If you absolutely must go somewhere, practice social distancing.
Wash your hands.

Stay strong, everyone.

Just a reminder to all of the students out there. Governor Reynolds has closed school buildings. She has not closed down school. Are you taking advantage of all those wonderful resources and activities your teachers are sending you? If not, why not? Learning needs to look different right now, but the opportunities are still there. Make your teachers happy!

The weather is beautiful, but the guidelines for getting through this pandemic remain the same.

Wash your hands.
Cover your cough.
Wash your hands.
Stay home. Stay home. Stay home. Stay home. Get the message?
